@node ADD "Main / Add"

        Will  add  a new Fidonet EchoMail conference to the list.
        The  cursor will go active in string gadget where you can
        enter the Fidonet TAGNAME of the conference that you wish
        to gate.  (Ie.  CSA_MISC)

        When  you  hit the 'return' key, you'll be prompted for a
        @{"Usenet Newsgroup" link USENETNEWG} (Ie.  comp.sys.amiga.misc).  The Fidonet
        messages will be converted to this Newsgroup.

        Next,  you'll  have to type in the NewsGroup @{"distribution" link DISTRIBUTION}
        field.   This  is  usually  'world' but you might want to
        change   it,   specially   if   you're   gating   private
        conferences.

        At last, if you wish to convert the charsets from Fidonet
        messages  to  other  formats (turning the 'Convert Chars'
        flag ON), you'll have to type in the name of the filename
        that will fit your needs best in the @{"Convert Table" link CONVTABLE} field.
        This  file is used by Convert and contains the convertion
        table.  This file can be edit for you.

        For  each  gated conference, there are two flags that can
        be set or not by you.  These are @{"Convert Chars" link CONVCHARS} and @{"Origin Lines" link ORIGINLIN}
        The  first  was  already explained and the second, if ON,
        will  cause  Fidonet  Origin  Lines present in the Usenet
        articles.
@endnode
@node REMOVE "Main / Remove"

        Will   remove   a  previously  entered  Fidonet  EchoMail
        conference.
@endnode
@node USENETNEWG "Main / Usenet NewsGroup"

        Here  you define the Newsgroup to where the correspondent
        Fidonet conference messages will be gated.
@endnode
@node DISTRIBUTION "Main / Distribution"

        To  understand  better  the  Usenet  Distribution  field,
        here's  a  copy  of  the  document RFC-1036 with protocol
        standards specs:

        ----
        This  line is used to alter the distribution scope of the
        message.   It  is  a  comma separated list similar to the
        "Newsgroups"   line.    User   subscriptions   are  still
        controlled  by  "Newsgroups",  but the message is sent to
        all   systems   subscribing  to  the  newsgroups  on  the
        "Distribution" line in addition to the "Newsgroups" line.
        For  the  message  to  be transmitted, the receiving site
        must normally receive one of the specified newsgroups AND
        must receive one of the specified distributions.  Thus, a
        message  concerning  a  car  for sale in New Jersey might
        have headers including:

               Newsgroups: rec.auto,misc.forsale
               Distribution: nj,ny

        so  that  it  would  only  go  to  persons subscribing to
        rec.auto  or  misc.   for  sale  within New Jersey or New
        York.   The  intent  of  this  header  is to restrict the
        distribution  of a newsgroup further, not to increase it.
        A  local newsgroup, such as nj.crazy-eddie, will probably
        not be propagated by hosts outside New Jersey that do not
        show  such  a  newsgroup  as  valid.  A follow-up message
        should  default  to  the  same "Distribution" line as the
        original  message,  but  the user can change it to a more
        limited  one,  or  escalate  the  distribution  if it was
        originally restricted and a more widely distributed reply
        is appropriate.
@endnode
@node CONVTABLE "Main / Convert Table"

        @{"Convert" link CONVERT} is an utility by Rainer Kopler that was specially
        built  to  convert  charsets  from  diferent platforms in
        ascii  files.   The  Convert  Tables  are  present  in  a
        directory  called  Scripts/.   Fido2UUCP  will search for
        Tables  in  this directory.  Read Convert docs.  for more
        information.
@endnode
@node  CONVERT  "Main / Convert"

        Convert is a powerful file conversion program.  It covers
        the  application  domain  of  all  ASCII conversion tools
        between  Amiga  and  MS-DOS or any other computer system.
        This  means, that file conversion with "Convert" does NOT
        affect  the  physical  format  of  a  file  but  only its
        contents.    Physical   conversion   is  not  subject  of
        "Convert" and thus assigned to tools like "CrossDOS".

        "Convert"  can be used to replace bytes or pairs of bytes
        in  a file by another byte or another pair of bytes or by
        nothing.  Therefore it can be used for tasks as follows:

        replacing TABs in an ASCII file with blank character(s)

        stripping controls in an ASCII file

        converting  ASCII-files  between Amiga and MS-DOS, MS-DOS
        and Amiga, Amiga and Mac, Mac and Sun, Amiga and Sun etc.

        What are "conversion descriptions" ?

        All  that  "Convert"  needs,  is  a  set  of "replacement
        records" which it can apply to its input files.  This set
        is in the following called "conversion description".  You
        can  create  your  individual  conversion descriptions by
        creating several "replacement records" with a text editor
        using  the  simple  syntax described in chapter 4.  These
        "records"  are  stored  to  a conversion description file
        which can be parsed by "Convert".

        The  draft  of specifying the conversion by a simple text
        file   makes  "Convert"  more  powerful  than  any  other
        conversion  tool  and  thus  allows  the  application  of
        "Convert" for almost all conversion problems.
@endnode
@node ORIGINLIN "Main / Origin Lines"

        If   set,   will   cause  Usenet  articles  to  have  the
        correspondent Fidonet message's origin lines.
@endnode
@node CONVCHARS "Main / Convert Chars"

        If  set,  will cause the Tosser to use @{"Convert" link CONVERT} with every
        tossed  message.   This  will, of course, slow down a bit
        the convertion time so use it only if you need it.
@endnode
@node LOG_FILE "Main / Log File"

        This   is   the  file  where  Fido2UUCP  will  write  log
        information.   It  is advisable that you delete this file
        regurarly  as  it may get too big.  Optionaly you can use
        NIL:  if you don't want any log file.
@endnode
@node UNPACKER "Main / Packet Unpacker"

        This  is  the  command used to unpack the packets for the
        Fake  Fidonet  System.   This must check with your mailer
        preferences.  (Ex:  C:Lha x, C:Unzip, etc..).
@endnode
@node ADDRESS "Main / Address"

        Here  you  can enter the 3D or 4D Fake Fidonet address to
        where  the messages from the conferences you wish to gate
        will  be  exported to.  If you're running a BBS, the most
        wise thing to do is to use a Point 4D address.

        Don't  forget to configure your system's mailer to export
        the conferences selected in Fido2UUCP to that Address.
@endnode
@node GATEHOST "Main / Local Hostname"

        This  will  be appended to the 'Path' field in the Usenet
        articles.   Be  sure  that  you set this to the same host
        that  you use to gate Newsgroups back to Fidonet.  If you
        don't, and you have a two way Gateway (Fidonet<->Usenet),
        you'll  probably  create  a loop.  Also, please write the
        address @{b}with@{ub} domain.
@endnode
@node RNEWS "Main / RNews Path"

        RNews  will  be  used  to  read the temporary batch files
        created  by Fido2UUCP.  As it's path may vary from system
        to system, I've added this field to increase flexibility.
@endnode
@node RMAIL "Main / RMail Path"

        RMail  is  by  your  UUCP  package to import private Mail
        trough  the  Net,  Fido2UUCP  uses  it  when  it's gating
        Fidonet  Netmail  to  the  Internet.  RMail is usually in
        UUCP:C/ but you can define any other path.
@endnode
