@node EMAILGATE "Main / E-Mail Gatename"

        This  a  definable  field for each gated area.  Converted
        messages  in the Usenet will have their From:  field with
        this  address.  This means that you can tell which path a
        message  will  take  when someone privatly replies to it.
        Examples  are  fidonet.org  but the following text from a
        Monalisa  Betatester,  Skip Watson, will clearly tell you
        why it isn't very wyse to use it:

        --- From Skip Watson:

            Well,   there   are  several  reasons.   One  is  the
        increased load on the fidonet.org machine.  What is going
        to  happen when the volume goes up by a factor of 1000 or
        more?   I  have  not exactly found this machine to be all
        that  reliable.  In tests where I've sent out 10 messages
        to  myself via that gate, I've gotten at most 6 back.  In
        one  test  I  only  got  1  out  of  10.   The  rest just
        disappeared.   Add  to  this  the  fact  that the fidonet
        community, at least around here, won't handle netmail for
        a  site unless that site has paid its echomail fees (even
        if it doesn't get echomail).

            Second, my feed sites insist that (like fidonet) if I
        bring  it in, I have to handle whatever mail it generates
        which is why I'm using Fred103 for email.

            Third,  it  reduces the number of gates.  In order to
        do  the  gating this way, your have a wildcarded address.
        You can't get that as a *.UUCP site.  You can't get it as
        a  member  of a subdomain.  Here in the US there are only
        two  ways  to get that, join the .US domain and request a
        wildcard  entry  or handle a real domain like aldhfn.org.
        I  think  the powers that be would rather limit the gates
        to  a  few well run ones than have hundreds of poorly run
        ones.   They  keep  remembering  the  problems  that  the
        Fidonet  gates  have created in the past and want to make
        sure those things don't happen again :-/.

            I've  been  having  to  deal  with  the local fidonet
        community where everyone wants to get a uucp and set up a
        gateway  instead  of using the one that already exists in
        their  own  town :-(.  having/running your own gateway is
        the latest status symbol for the Fidonet "children".

        --- End.

        So  the best option is to use your own system to gate the
        Mail back to Fidonet.  You can use UUCP2Fido for this.
@endnode
@node ADD_ACCEPT "E-Mail / Add Acceptable"

        Will  add  an  entry to the "Acceptable" list.  Wildcards
        are  accepted.   Fidonet  addresses can have the 3D or 4D
        format.   This  list  of  systems will have access to the
        E-Mail  services  unless denied in the "Rejectable" list.
        Examples are *:*/*.*, 2:*/*.*, 2:361/*, etc...

        Pay atention to entries like "*:*/*.*".  This will reject
        the address 1:2/345 and accept the address 1:2/345.6.  If
        you want to give access to everyone, you'll have to write
        and  entry  like "*:*/*".  To understand Wilcards better,
        imagine  you're  in  CLI  and you type "dir #?.#?".  This
        will  only show  you files that have a "." in their name.
        If you type "dir #?", you'll get everything.
@endnode
@node REMOVE_ACCEPT "E-Mail / Remove Acceptable"

        Will  remove  a  previsouly entered and selected address.
        See @{"Add Acceptable" link ADD_ACCEPT} for more details.
@endnode
@node ADD_REJECT "E-Mail / Add Rejectable"

        Will add an entry to the "Rejectable" list.  Wilcards are
        accepted.   Fidonet  addresses  can  have  the  3D  or 4D
        format.   This  is the list of systems who access will be
        denied  from  the "Acceptable" list.  Systems that aren't
        in  the  "Acceptable"  list  don't  have  any  efect here
        because  they aren't even being accept for the beggining.
        The  "Acceptable" list has priority over the "Rejectable"
        list.
@endnode
@node REMOVE_REJECT "E-Mail / Remove Rejectable"

        Will  remove  a  previsouly entered and selected address.
        See @{"Add Rejectable" link ADD_REJECT} for more details.
@endnode
@node OUTBOUND "E-Mail / OutBound Directory"

        This  is  the  directory  where the Fido2UUCP Tosser will
        search  for  packets  the match the fake @{"gateway address" link ADDRESS}.
        This  is usually Mail:OutBound/ but it's nothing wrong if
        you set this to another path.  This used both by EchoMail
        and Netmail routines.
@endnode
@node INBOUND "E-Mail / InBound Directory"

        This  is where PKTGenerator, when used by Fido2UUCP, will
        store NetMail messages.  At the moment, the only messages
        stored  here  will  be warnings of bad usage when someone
        tries  to  gate  Netmail without authorization or doesn't
        obeids to Monalisa's basic.  This will only happen if the
        @{"Reply Bad NetMail" link REP_BAD_NETMAIL} flag in ON.
@endnode
@node REP_BAD_NETMAIL "E-Mail / Reply Bad NetMail"

        If  this  flag  is  ON, Fido2UUCP will warn back the user
        with a @{"Reply Message" link REPLY_MESG} telling him that he tried to use the
        gateway  improperly  when  he  does so.  At the same time
        Fido2UUCP  denies  to gate NetMail to Usenet/Internet, it
        will log the event and warn the sender.

        To  do  this,  Fido2UUCP will use PKTGenerator externaly.
        Because  of  this, you can configure some parameters that
        will  be  parsed to it.  This is done by editing the file
        MONALISA:Preferences/BounceMail.prefs  which  is  nothing
        more  than  a  configuration file for PKTGen.  Only a few
        parameters are used though.  These are:

        - From name.
        - Message subject.
        - Origin line.
        - Inbound directory for Netmail.
        - Origin address.

        A  sample  file  is  provided  with monalisa distribution
        archive.   To edit this file, you just need need to click
        twice the 'Config BadMesgs' icon in Fido2UUCP directory.
@endnode
@node REPLY_MESG "E-Mail / Reply Message"

        Here  you  select  a text file which is nothing more than
        the  message  that will be sent to the user that tried to
        use  the  gateway  improperly.   Some information will be
        added  at  the  end  of this message, that is, to who the
        message  was  ment  to,  the  subject of the message, the
        arrive  date  at  your system and carbon and blind carbon
        copies  information.   An  example message is included in
        your Monalisa distribuiton archive.
@endnode
@node SCAN_ECHOMAIL "E-Mail / Scan EchoMail"

        This  is a special feature of Fido2UUCP suggested by some
        Betatesters.   It's  ment  to  be used by those who don't
        have  access  to  Fidonet  NetMail.   If this flag is ON,
        Fido2UUCP  will gate @{b}EchoMail@{ub} messages to the Internet if
        they  start with a To:  <address> line, then optional Cc:
        and  Bcc:  lines and finally a blank line to separate the
        header  from  the  message  itself.   The  security lists
        (Accept/Reject) will also act over this feature.
@endnode
@node EMAIL_NOTES "E-Mail / Important notes"

        All  NetMail  going  to  the fake system has to be either
        included with EchoMail packets or in HOLD to that system,
        that  is,  packets  for it in the OutBound directory have
        the z.net.nod.pt.OUT format.

        Optionaly,  NetMail  may  be  included  in  your EchoMail
        packets.   Some mailers process Netmail this way.  Tosser
        will interpret these as well.
@endnode
@node HELP_KEY "General / The HELP key"

        Pressing  the  HELP  key will cause Fido2UUCP to show you
        Fido2UUCP documentation in AmigaGuide format.
@endnode
@node TZNAME "Time Zone Name"

        Default  is  GMT  but  if exists the environment variable
        TZNANE,  Fido2UUCP  will  use  it  instead.  Articles and
        E-Mail headers use this string in the "Date:" line.

        To set this variable type "setenv TZNAME=your_time_zone".
        Ex:  "setenv TZNAME=EST"

        The  best  thing  to  do  is  to  add  this  line to your
        s:user-startup  script  or to copy the ENV:TZNAME file to
        your ENVARC:  directory.

        Other  packages use this environment variable so it might
        be not necessary to do anything.
@endnode
